ngful probability that unit could work (20%) or system testing is needed (10%).\n\nEnvironment variable precedence is straightforward logic that unit testing handles well (90% confident), since it's just about override ordering. YAML syntax error reporting similarly depends on the parser providing line numbers, which unit testing verifies adequately (85% confident). For directory and file creation on first run, the test must verify that operations happen in the correct sequence—unit mocks might allow any order without catching real issues, making integration testing more appropriate (70% confident), though unit could work if carefully designed (20%). ical path to the missing key.\n\n2. **XDG_CONFIG_HOME affects path resolution**\n   - Test: Set XDG_CONFIG_HOME to a temporary directory and verify the loader reads from that location instead of the default ~/.config path.\n   - Description: Confirms the loader respects the XDG_CONFIG_HOME environment variable for config file discovery.\n\n3. **Environment variable overrides file config**\n   - Test: Configure a value in the file, set a matching TOOL_* environment variable, and verify the environment variable takes precedence.\n   - Description: Ensures environment variables override corresponding file-based configuration values.\n\n4. **YAML syntax error includes line number**\n   - Test: Provide a YAML string with invalid indentation and verify the error message includes the line number where the error was detected.\n   - Description: Confirms syntax errors in the config file are reported with their location for easier debugging.\n\n5. **Create config directory and defaults file on first run**\n   - Test: Point to a nonexistent config directory, call the loader, and verify both the directory and a defaults file are created with correct content.\n   - Description: Ensures the loader initializes the config environment automatically on first use.\n\nI'm questioning whether behavior 2 really needs an integration test. A unit test could mock the environment variable and file system calls to verify the path resolution logic works correctly without needing actual directories.\n\nFor instance, I could set XDG_CONFIG_HOME via environment patching, mock the file operations, invoke the loader, and assert that `open()` was called with the expected path containing that variable. This would catch cases where the loader ignores the environment variable or constructs the wrong path. The test would verify path construction logic without relying on the filesystem, and Python's pathlib handles edge cases like tilde expansion automatically.\n\nHowever, a pure mock approach has limitations. If the bug involves subtle path construction failures—say, incorrect string concatenation or path joining—the mock might not surface these issues if it's too permissive about which paths it accepts. An integration test using a real filesystem would be more thorough, actually exercising the full path resolution and file access chain rather than just verifying that the right path string was passed to `open()`.\n\nAdjusting my confidence: Unit tests work for straightforward cases like ignoring the environment variable entirely, but integration testing is safer for catching edge cases in path handling. I'd estimate Unit at 0.25, Integration at 0.70, System at 0.05.\n\nI should also verify the `plan_consistent` field—whether my test descriptions actually require the level I've chosen or if they'd pass at a lower one. For the missing key error message, a unit test with mocked file operations is sufficient, so that's consistent. For the XDG_CONFIG_HOME behavior, I need to set up a temporary directory structure and verify the loader actually reads from the right location, which genuinely requires integration-level testing.\n\nThe environment variable override test works fine at the unit level with mocks. The YAML syntax error test just needs the parsing logic without any filesystem involvement. For the directory creation